<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JUL 94 / Code on property leases proposed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON DAVIES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government has decided not to legislate against commercial-leasing
practices after a one-year consultation that followed widespread criticism
by tenants, Simon Davies writes.
However it is urging the property industry to set up its own code of
practice covering the controversial areas of upward-only rent reviews,
confidentiality clauses and dispute resolution procedures.
Mr Tony Baldry, environment minister, said: 'It is evident that the market
is now providing a greater variety of lease terms'. The proposed code would
encourage greater flexibility. He was replying to a written question from
Mrs Angela Browning, Tory MP for Tiverton, on the conclusions of the
consultation paper.
Concerns had been expressed in parliament that the practice of upward-only
rent reviews was a significant contributor to inflation. Mr Baldry said:
'Whilst the relative bargaining strengths of the parties will depend on the
state of the market, it is not clear that occupiers fully appreciate the
strength of their own bargaining positions.'
</TEXT>
