<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JUL 94 / Labour to stress 'green' economics
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES and KEVIN BROWN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Labour yesterday pledged to put greater emphasis on the environment in
government, particularly where it can create new jobs and produce a more
sustainable economy.
The party sets out an approach to environmental issues in a new policy
document which relies heavily on government action, particularly in
transport and energy.
Mr Chris Smith, environment spokesman, said: 'We have tried to integrate the
environment into a whole range of policy areas. We view the environment not
just as a challenge, but also an opportunity.'
In a policy paper, In Trust for Tomorrow, Labour proposes to create jobs by
encouraging energy efficiency conversions in homes; training young people to
help clean up the environment; and promoting environmental industries which
supply clean technologies and 'green' products. It would also offer
protection to 'whistle-blowers' who reveal breaches of environmental law by
their employers.
The party acknowledges for the first time that increased protection for the
environment could lead to a lower rate of growth in gross domestic product.
The document says: 'A sustainable economic policy will aim to optimise
environmentally beneficial activity, recognising that there are limits to
the pollution that can be safely emitted, and that the consumption of
non-renewable resources needs to be matched by the development of renewable
technologies.'
Labour would aim to change the national accounting system by 2000. A
reformed measure of national income would initially be published alongside
GDP figures.
Transport policy would be reversed, with a shift of investment from road
building to public transport. A moratorium on new road schemes would be
declared pending a review, and it would aim to double the amount of
long-haul freight carried by rail.
The party would stress improving the energy efficiency of homes with
incentives which could create up to 50,000 jobs in the building sector.
Labour would also support the coal industry by promoting clean-coal
technology and halting nuclear-power construction, and set a target of 10
per cent electricity generation from renewable sources by 2010.
For the private individual, a Labour government would establish a set of
environmental rights, such as clean air and drinking water, and access to
open land. People would also have the right to compensation for
environmental damage.
The document received a broad welcome from the environmental lobby. The
Council for the Protection of Rural England said Labour had 'woken up to the
importance of having an effective environment policy'. Friends of the Earth
welcomed Labour's recognition that the environment could create jobs.
However, the Road Haulage Association attacked the document, saying it
played down the environmental improvements made in transport and exaggerated
the problems.
Berrymans, a firm of solicitors specialising in pollution cases, said the
policy had failed to deal adequately with environmental liability.
</TEXT>
