<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JUL 94 / London service sector sees jobs fall
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN TETT, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The outlook for employment in London's service sector has grown gloomier in
the last three months, according to a survey by the London Chamber of
Commerce.
The proportion of service-sector businesses that say employment has risen,
compared to those who say it has fallen, has dropped to a negative balance
of 13. In the last quarterly survey in March there was a positive balance of
28 in the proportion of companies reporting a pick-up in employment.
Meanwhile, the proportion of service-sector businesses expecting employment
to pick up in the next three months has also dropped significantly, to a
negative balance of three.
This decline took place even though export optimism in the sector rose
sharply in the last three months. Overall business confidence is now at its
highest level for five years in the sector.
The report, which surveyed 344 business employing about 330,000 people in
greater London, notes that export confidence in manufacturing also rose.
However domestic deliveries fell and overall business confidence dipped
slightly, although the balances in both sectors remained positive.
The balance of manufacturing companies reporting increased employment has
now risen to zero, up from a negative balance of minus five in the last
quarter.
London Chamber of Commerce and Industry quarterly economic report and
survey. 33 Queen St, London EC4R 1AP. Pounds 12 members, Pounds 18
non-members.
</TEXT>
