<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JUL 94 / Prison-building programme 'hit by delays'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The extensive prison-building and modernisation programme in England and
Wales has been dogged by cost overruns and delays, the National Audit Office
says in a report published today.
The public expenditure watchdog found that costs exceeded estimates in every
one of the seven new prison projects - all completed since 1991 - examined
for the report. There were also overruns on 15 refurbishment programmes.
Total construction costs for the seven prisons were Pounds 475m - Pounds
78.9m more than the estimated costs. With Woodhill, near Milton Keynes, the
cost of Pounds 102.3m was 31 per cent over the tender price.
The time taken to build the seven prisons varied between three years and
eight-and-a-half years, the report says.
On all 15 of the refurbishment projects, the final cost exceeded the
contract price by 10 per cent or more. Seven of the 15 were completed in
time, with significant delays on some of the rest.
The watchdog says however that the building and modernisation programme is
the greatest effort to improve conditions and provide accommodation since
the 19th century.
It also commends the Prison Service for reducing the average time to build a
prison from seven years to four years.
Delays and extra costs were incurred because of changes in design - often
the fault of contractors - and improvements required by the service, some of
them prompted by incidents at other prisons.
The report puts the blame for many of the problems on the service for
overloading project managers. The service gives managers a workload that
leaves them little time for adequate financial and managerial control.
It also says that Treasury rules limiting the scope for carrying forward
unspent money constrain effective management of prison building works.
Control of Prison Building Projects. HMSO. Pounds 8.95.
</TEXT>
