<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JUL 94 / Merseyside body lifts performance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY, Northern Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The controversial Merseyside Development Corporation yesterday told MPs it
had met or exceeded all government targets set for it in the year ended
March 31. The targets are the main means of measuring performance among the
10 development corporations.
The Liverpool-based corporation, which was set up in 1981 to regenerate
Mersey docklands, has been under fire from the Commons public accounts
committee over losses of nearly Pounds 700,000 on an opera concert staged to
celebrate a tall ships regatta in 1992. The committee will report in the
autumn.
The corporation's annual report says it has reclaimed 47 acres of land in
the last year, built nearly five miles of new roads and 402 houses,
developed more than 750,000 sq ft of commercial floor space, secured 2,753
jobs and attracted Pounds 37m of private-sector investment.
In addition it has also attracted 112 new companies into its mainly
waterfront areas and has let more than 720,000 sq ft of space - 9 per cent
up on 1992-93. Indirect investment in plant and equipment by private-sector
companies rose 24 per cent to Pounds 43.2m.
The opera concert was contracted to an independent company formed by the
corporation's local public-relations consultant. No other tenders were asked
for. When ticket sales failed to materialise, the corporation had to inject
about Pounds 400,000 to save the concert. The company later collapsed,
leaving creditors bearing most of the losses.
</TEXT>
