<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JUL 94 / Nuclear privatisation call renewed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES, Resources Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Scottish Nuclear, the state-owned utility, has revived its plea to be
privatised.
In a submission to the government's nuclear review yesterday the company
said its long-term future could only be secured if it was put on the same
commercial footing as other electricity generators.
Mr Robin Jeffrey, chief executive, said the government would not provide
money to build further nuclear power stations - funds would have to come
from the private sector.
Although Scottish Nuclear came out in favour of privatisation before its
English counterpart, Nuclear Electric, it had appeared to back off because
of the practical problems of adapting nuclear power for the private sector.
But Mr Jeffrey said yesterday that he felt these problems had now been
clearly identified - and could be resolved. His company hoped to be
privatised by the end of 1996.
Scottish Nuclear is proposing that it be split into two parts. One would
contain its closed Hunterston A Magnox station and the associated
liabilities, as well as past liabilities for reprocessing fuel from its two
active advanced gas-cooled reactors (AGRs).
The financial provisions already made for decommissioning Hunterston A would
be put into a segregated fund, which would take over full responsibility for
the station.
The other part - which would become the company to be privatised - would
consist of the two AGR stations and the provisions made for their
decommissioning costs. Mr Jeffrey said this company would be able to operate
commercially, particularly if the government approved its plan to put spent
fuel into a dry store instead of sending it for expensive reprocessing.
Mr Jeffrey said he believed the wholesale price of electricity would rise
from 2.5p to 3p per unit by the end of the decade as supplies of fossil
fuels became tighter.
The environmental costs of fossil fuels would also add between 0.4p and 0.8p
to each unit. Against this, Scottish Nuclear estimated that it would be able
to get its existing costs down to 2.5p a unit this year, with any newly
built plant producing at 2.9p.
Unlike Nuclear Electric, which wants to build a new nuclear station at
Sizewell as soon as possible, Scottish Nuclear has no need for extra
capacity until 2011. But Mr Jeffrey suggested that a privatised company
might not build a nuclear station: it could build whatever was appropriate.
</TEXT>
