<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JUL 94 / Cost targets planned to curb NHS bureaucracy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government is to launch a fresh initiative to counter growing
bureaucracy in the National Health Service by setting out broad targets for
management spending by trust hospitals and community health groups.
Amid growing concern about the increase in the number of NHS managers,
ministers will reveal that the average administrative costs incurred by NHS
trusts over the past year are between 3.5 per cent and 6 per cent of their
total budgets.
The Department of Health intends to use this figure as a guide to how much
each trust chief executive should spend on management. Earlier this year Mrs
Virginia Bottomley, the health secretary, admitted that some trusts spent as
much as 8.6 per cent of their total pay bill on administration, and said it
needed to be reduced.
The recommendations will come in a hitherto confidential report produced by
the Department of Health, the Audit Commission and the Trust Federation,
which should be published later this year.
But it is unlikely to satisfy critics in the Labour party and health unions
who argue that the purchaser/provider reforms in the NHS have led to more an
bureaucrats.
Concern over the increase in bureaucracy followed the publication of figures
last year showing that the number of NHS managers rose by nearly 25 per cent
in 1992.
Mr John Redwood, the Welsh secretary, recently embarrassed the government by
referring to the 'restlessness among medical staff about the number of men
in grey suits'.
The government does not intend to enforce strict guidelines for spending on
management. It believes that publication of figures on the average
administrative expenditure by trusts will exert strong public pressure on
those which exceed the figure.
It will be a criminal offence for a drug company to offer expensive gifts
and for doctors to accept them under regulations presented to parliament
yesterday.
The regulations implement the European directive on the advertising of
medicines. Inexpensive items relevant to the practice of medicine or
pharmacy remain allowed.
</TEXT>
