<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JUL 94 / Row over cash for questions probe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A row broke out at Westminster yesterday after four MPs with extensive
outside interests were proposed to sit on the committee charged with
investigating the so-called 'cash for questions' affair.
The 17 MPs selected to serve on the Committee of Privileges had between them
18 paid directorships, eight consultancies and six sponsorship arrangements
with trade unions or other bodies.
Just two of the proposed committee members, both Conservatives, had nothing
to declare in the most recent register of members' interests.
One Labour MP - Mr Dale Campbell-Savours - immediately claimed that the
public would not have 'very much confidence' in a probe conducted by such a
committee.
But this view was rebutted by Sir James Spicer, who was among the nine
Tories nominated. 'Do you want people on a committee like this to be
virtually eunuchs who do nothing at all except haunt the House of Commons?'
he asked.
The inquiry will focus on the case of two Conservative MPs who were
suspended from their posts as junior ministerial aides after reports that
they were prepared to accept Pounds 1,000 for tabling parliamentary
questions. But some Tories are worried the probe could lead to a fundamental
reassessment of MPs' outside interests.
Labour MPs last night blocked attempts to nod through the appointment of
those named, forcing a debate on the subject today and making it less likely
the committee will be able to meet for the first time before the recess.
The bulk of the directorships and consultancies held by those proposed for
the committee were shared between four senior Tory MPs: Sir Marcus Fox,
chairman of the backbench 1922 committee; Sir Peter Hordern, Sir Cranley
Onslow, a past 1922 committee chairman; and Sir Giles Shaw.
Six of the seven Labour MPs are sponsored by trade unions or other bodies,
the exception being Mr Tony Benn, MP for Chesterfield. The two proposed
members who had nothing to declare in the most recent register were Mr Tony
Newton, leader of the Commons, and Mr John Ward.
The full list of those proposed was as follows: Sir Nicholas Lyell
(attorney-general); Mr David Alton (Lib Dem Liverpool Mossley Hill); Mr Tony
Benn (Lab Chesterfield); Sir Marcus Fox (C Shipley); Sir Peter Hordern (C
Horsham); Mr Doug Hoyle (Lab Warrington North); Mr Bill Michie (Lab
Sheffield Heeley); Sir David Mitchell (C Hampshire North West); Mr Alf
Morris (Lab Manchester Wythenshawe); Mr John Morris (shadow
attorney-general); Mr Tony Newton (Leader of the Commons); Sir Cranley
Onslow (C Woking); Sir Giles Shaw (C Pudsey); Mr Peter Shore (Lab Bethnal
Green and Stepney); Sir James Spicer (C Dorset West); Mr John Ward (C
Poole), and Mr Alan Williams (Lab Swansea West).
</TEXT>
