<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JUL 94 / Most charities to benefit from eased accounts rules
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Most charities will face lighter accounting requirements under proposals of
a voluntary sector deregulation taskforce which were accepted by the
government yesterday.
Charities with an annual income of less than Pounds 10,000 will in future
satisfy their legal obligations by producing simplified trustees' annual
reports and accounts in line with Charity Commission guidance.
More than 90 per cent of charity income goes to the biggest 10 per cent of
charities, and some two-thirds of the sector will benefit from being able to
produce simpler reports and accounts. Ministers have also agreed in
principle that the income threshold at which bigger charities' accounts must
be audited rather than independently examined should rise from Pounds
100,000 to Pounds 250,000.
The government has fully or partially accepted 72 of 189 recommendations in
the taskforce's report. A further 60 are under review. Recommendations
accepted cover a wide range of issues, from easing restrictions on obtaining
permits for charitable collections to agreeing to clarify the application of
health and safety legislation to village halls and community centres.
Ministers intend to extend the small-business litmus test - under which the
likely impact on small businesses is taken into account before new
regulations are framed - to include the effect on charities.
Britain's voluntary sector has a turnover of about Pounds 16bn a year and
faces many of the same regulation issues as business.
The government wants charities to play a growing role in delivering services
under contract to public authorities, and hopes that the changes accepted
yesterday will lead to increased efficiency.
There will however be disappointment in the sector about recommendations the
government has rejected. A call to lessen the restrictions on trustees'
scope to invest funds has been turned down, although the Treasury said it is
'considering the case for reform'. Charities made little progress in their
efforts to to raise the problems faced from a Pounds 335m annual bill for
irrecoverable value added tax.
</TEXT>
