<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JUL 94 / World Trade News: WTO chief contender with trade in his
veins - Guy de Jonquieres interviews South Korean Kim Chul-su who is seeking
to head the new world body
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GUY DE JONQUIERES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Kim Chul-su, South Korea's trade minister, is not a natural
attention-seeker. Soft-spoken, courteous and discreetly attired, he looks
every inch the product of his 20-year career as an influential government
technocrat.
But in the next few weeks, the 53-year-old Mr Kim will be pounding the
campaign trail, canvassing support in ministries around the globe for his
bid to become head of the World Trade Organisation, which is due to succeed
the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade next year.
Australia, eager to emphasise its Asian links, has already come out in his
favour, and he is optimistic about winning backing in the rest of the
region. He is more guarded about the attitudes of the US and the EU, whose
support, he acknowledges, will be crucial.
He bases his claim to the WTO job, first, on Korea's spectacular economic
development, which is emblematic of Asia's rapidly growing importance in the
global economy and international trade.
He relates with pride how, in three decades, his country has risen from
poverty to the stage where it is ready to join the Organisation for Economic
Co-operation and Development, the Paris-based 'rich man's club'.
His second claim is his long specialisation in international trade affairs.
He participated in the Uruguay Round and has represented Korea in many
bilateral trade negotiations with the US, the European Union and Japan.
'I have the feel of the trade policies of industrialised and developing
countries,' he says, adding that Korea's trade is equally divided between
them. 'I think I can deal with trade and investment issues in an impartial
way.'
The US-educated Mr Kim, who speaks fluent English, is respected as an astute
negotiator in support of his government's interests. 'He is a tough cookie
who is always on top of his brief,' says a senior European official.
Other observers, however, were less impressed by his chairmanship of a key
Uruguay Round committee. 'Much of the nitty-gritty work was done by others,'
says an official in Geneva. 'You couldn't say he made the difference between
success and failure.'
Mr Kim believes his penchant for technical detail would be valuable in
getting the WTO running smoothly. 'The leader should be ready to act as
conciliator and mediator. In that capacity, he has to know the details of
trade problems. Willingness to work with details is very important to the
job,' he says.
His skills at settling international disputes were severely tested in the
late 1980s, when US threats of trade sanctions against Seoul inflamed
relations with Washington and outraged Korean public opinion. 'But in the
end, we were able to solve the problem in a relatively calm way,' he says.
That experience left him with a deep aversion to bilateral trade offensives.
'There is always political resistance when a big country tries to pressure
people in a smaller country to accepting its own standards and preferences,'
he says.
Mr Kim is reluctant to enunciate any sweeping vision for the future of the
WTO, saying it will have plenty to do implementing the Uruguay Round and
negotiating the entry of about 20 new members.
He is equally reticent about how he would handle politically contentious
questions, such as the links between trade, the environment and workers'
rights, arguing that more research is needed to define an 'intellectual
basis' for policy-making.
He stands 'somewhere in the middle' of the debate on workers' rights and
trade, which has put the US and many developing countries at bitter odds.
However, he would like the WTO to study how to help the very poorest
countries benefit more from international trade.
Though such cautious attitudes may not impress those who believe the WTO
needs charismatic, high-profile leadership, they are unlikely to arouse
hostility, either.
More controversial may be Korea's reputation for being slow to remove trade
barriers. In a recent survey of international companies, it emerged as the
most protectionist country in the Asia-Pacific region and the most hostile
towards inward investment.
Mr Kim concedes Korea may have 'a negative image', but considers it unfair.
'One would be hard-pressed to name a country which has moved so fast to
liberalise in the past 15 years,' he says, adding that the process has
recently accelerated.
He also insists that critics - particularly in Europe - are partly to blame
for ignoring opportunities in Asia. 'European governments and businessmen
need to be more aggressive,' he says.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>CHZ  Switzerland, West Europe.
    KRZ  South Korea, Asia.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
