<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JUL 94 / US envoy urges UN force to end Rwanda tragedy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LESLIE CRAWFORD
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NAIROBI
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A special US envoy to Rwanda said yesterday he would urge the dispatch of a
large United Nations peacekeeping force to convince millions of Hutus who
have fled the country that it would be safe to return under Rwanda's new
Tutsi-dominated government.
Mr Brian Atwood, who will brief President Bill Clinton tomorrow on the
humanitarian catastrophe caused by the flight of over 1m Hutus into Zaire,
expressed confidence in Rwanda's new leaders, the rebel Rwandan Patriotic
Front, which declared victory this week after a four-year guerrilla war
against a Hutu government and army.
'We have been working hard behind the scenes to encourage the formation of a
moderate, mixed Hutu-Tutsi government,' Mr Atwood said in Nairobi. 'We are
prepared to work with them to consolidate peace and begin the reconstruction
of the country.'
The Tutsi-led RPF yesterday installed a new government in the capital Kigali
which includes a Hutu president, Mr Pasteur Bizimungu, and a Hutu prime
minister, Mr Faustin Twagiramungu. Its immediate problem is how to win
legitimacy in the eyes of Rwanda's Hutu majority, many members of whom
participated in the slaughter of the Tutsi population following the death of
President Juvenal Habyarimana in an air crash in April.
Several western governments, including Belgium and the US, have now pledged
to work with Rwanda's new government.
France, which sent an intervention force to Rwanda earlier this month
yesterday acknowledged Rwandan rebels had effectively won the war. Mr Alain
Juppe, foreign minister, said Paris would negotiate with the victors on an
end to its intervention.
Even if the UN troops are deployed rapidly, Mr Atwood believes it will take
several months before the right psychological environment can be created to
persuade the Hutu population to return.
In RPF-controlled areas, for example, Mr Atwood said rebels were holding
Hutus in encampments against their will.
But Mr Atwood's immediate concern, like that of all international relief
agencies, is how to deal with a refugee crisis of unprecedented proportions
on Rwanda's western border with Zaire. The UN High Commissioner for Refugees
says there are 1m refugees in the Zairean border town of Goma, and about
100,000 more in Bukavu to the south. Yesterday there were reports that
400,000 Rwandans had flooded into another Zairean town, Uvira.
'It's really an exodus of a nation. The whole country is coming out of its
borders. We can't cope,' Mr Panos Moumtzis, an UNHCR spokesman, said.
Medecins Sans Frontieres, the medical charity, warned that thousands of
people faced almost certain death due to the logistical impossibilities of
meeting the needs of the biggest flow of refugees in contemporary history.
Mr Atwood also fears Rwanda's defeated Hutu troops, who have also fled into
Zaire, might attempt to regroup and invade Rwanda, or wage a war of
attrition against the new Tutsi-led regime.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>RWZ  Rwanda, Africa.
    KEZ  Kenya, Africa.
</CN>
