<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JUL 94 / A changing Taiwan wants welfare without the tears:
Traditional care systems need replacing but policymakers want to avoid the
west's mistakes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURA TYSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Like its east Asian neighbours, Taiwan is grappling with how to balance the
growing need for social services such as healthcare and old-age support
against fears of turning its vibrant economy into a hypertaxed welfare
state.
Taiwan's parliament yesterday approved a universal health insurance scheme
which is due to come into effect from January. And the establishment of a
national pension scheme is to top the legislative agenda during the autumn
session.
The health scheme will be state-run and will be 90 per cent financed by
employer and employee contributions, with the state picking up the rest.
Total healthcare expenditure is projected to be NTDollars 270bn (Pounds
6.5bn) in the first year.
Taiwan is going the way of most industrialised countries. Rising incomes,
shifting demographics and changing social structures are straining the
capacity of traditional family-based care. And with per capita gross
national product having risen from Dollars 145 in 1951 to more than Dollars
11,000 this year, there is more money around to pay for good care than there
are opportunities to get it.
In 1993 existing government-run health, labour and retirement insurance
schemes covered just more than half Taiwan's population of nearly 21m.
In recent months, Taiwan's medical establishment has been rocked by a spate
of scandals revealing the widespread practice among doctors, whose salaries
are low by most comparable countries' standards, of accepting bribes for
services.
Entrepreneurial solutions have emerged to fill the void left by a government
struggling to keep up with the welfare demands of an industrialised society.
But Taiwan, which prides itself on having probably the most equitable
distribution of wealth among Asian countries, is anxious not to allow
quality health services to become the preserve of the rich.
Under the state-run health insurance scheme, employers will pay 60 per cent
of their employees' premiums and the employees 30 per cent. The state will
pick up the remaining 10 per cent as well as the administrative costs.
But the government's burden will be significantly higher because it must
subsidise a large part of the premiums, including those for government
employees, veterans, the self-employed and low-income groups.
Mr Chan Huo-sheng of National Taiwan University's graduate institute of
sociology is pessimistic about the health plan, which he describes as a
hybrid version of the US, Canadian and British systems.
'Based on my experience in Britain, I am very much in favour of universal
health insurance. The difference is in Britain, general practitioners are
government employees. But here doctors are privately employed and the
hospitals are privately run.
'So doctors, who are a powerful pressure group, will be bargaining with the
government over fees and services,' Mr Chan argues. 'And here we don't have
a strong sense of ethics in the medical profession. There are problems with
wastage of resources, problems with hong bao' - red envelopes - a reference
to the institutionalised bribery of doctors for preferential services.
In the absence of a mechanism to keep a lid on the costs of providing
healthcare, expenditures will escalate endlessly, the government will be
forced to shoulder a heavier burden and taxpayers will have to pay more to
keep the system afloat in what will became a vicious circle, he predicts.
The ruling Nationalist party wanted to push the programme through quickly
for political reasons without subjecting it to sufficient debate and study,
says legislator Parris Chang of the leading opposition party, the Democratic
Progressive Party (DPP).
Demographic forces are also driving the need for a modern national old-age
pension scheme. The country's population growth rate fell below 1 per cent
in 1993 for the first time and is projected to reach zero in 2035.
At the same time the population is greying rapidly. The median age is
forecast to rise to 42.6 in 2036 from 28.6 in 1993, and the percentage of
the population aged 65 and over to 21.57 from 6.93.
The tradition of extended multi-generational families living under one roof
is fast giving way to the nuclear family, leaving greater numbers of the
elderly to fend for themselves on a day-to-day basis. Mr Chen Chao-nan, a
researcher at the Academia Sinica, a government think-tank, estimates that
one-third of Taiwanese 65 and older now live alone, twice as many as in the
mid-1970s.
In addition, women - historically the primary carers - have entered the
labour force in unprecedented numbers. In 1992 women made up 37.7 per cent
of the workforce, compared with 27 per cent in 1965.
'Basically we're seeing a sharp reduction in informal social support
systems,' said Mr Chen. 'In addition to national health insurance, we need
home care systems and nursing homes for those elderly whose family are no
longer able to physically care for them.'
The DPP has proposed a pension scheme loosely modelled on the American
social security system, under which workers would pay into the scheme and
begin collecting once they reached 65. Under existing comprehensive schemes,
covered workers receive a lump sum payout upon retirement.
The ruling party has yet to produce its own pension plan proposal, but it is
likely to be similar to the DPP's.
'Both parties favour self-financing systems, as they fear too much
government intervention will lead to waste and inefficiency,' says Mr Ho
Dwanfan, director of the DPP's social issues department. 'The widely held
view is that welfare will make people lazy. Everyone is very much afraid of
becoming like Britain - the economy goes downhill and everybody blames the
welfare system.'
Articles on the welfare impact of a greying society in Hong Kong and
Singapore appeared in the Financial Times last Thursday and Friday
respectively
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>TWZ  Taiwan, Asia.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9441 Administration of Social and Manpower Programs.
    P9431 Administration of Public Health Programs.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>GOVT  Government News.
    CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 4
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT943-13403</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-EGTEBAAZFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940720
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JUL 94 / Argentina seeks to trim civil service
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CARMEN PIGNOTTI and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BUENOS AIRES
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Argentina plans to cut civil service costs by 10 per cent, and introduce
tighter tax controls and a range of export incentives, according to an
outline of the 1995 budget bill, released yesterday by the economy ministry.
However, based on average consumer and wholesale price inflation of 3.5 per
cent and GDP growth of 6.5 per cent in 1995, the budget promises to step up
spending on state-funded health and education.
The budget statement did not estimate the effect of these measures on total
public spending. However, in earlier estimates, the government had forecast
1995 total public sector spending at 81.9bn pesos (Pounds 52.5bn) - roughly
26.3 per cent of GDP - compared with 78.8bn pesos budgeted for this year, or
26.5 per cent of GDP.
The peso is at par with the US dollar.
Previous official figures have projected a federal revenue surplus of 4.5bn
pesos for the current year, and of 3.18bn-3.23bn pesos for 1995.
The government is under pressure to rein in public spending if it wishes to
maintain its economic reforms and sustain the dollar-peso parity established
in April 1991.
Mr Daniel Artana, chief economist at FIEL, an economic think-tank funded by
Argentina's leading companies, said the general feeling that the peso is
overvalued would be eased by the budget.
He also suggested that the tax revenue estimates were realistic. Tax
collection had increased by about 17 per cent in the first half of 1994,
compared with the equivalent period of 1993.
This rise took place despite cuts in payroll taxes, with most of it coming
from increased income tax collection and a crackdown on tax dodging. Tax
revenue has been forecast to rise to 30.8bn pesos next year, from an
estimated 26.5bn pesos in 1994.
The draft budget made no provisions for general pay rises, keeping salaries
tied to productivity levels in all departments. The cuts in civil service
costs are planned to fall largely on travel budgets and diplomatic postings.
The economy ministry estimated exports next year would rise by 13 per cent
to Dollars 17.4bn and put the trade deficit at Dollars 4.3bn. This year's
trade shortfall has been estimated to reach a new record of Dollars
4.5bn-Dollars 6bn, topping last year's Dollars 3.7bn deficit.
Reuter reports: Intelligence experts from Israel, Spain and other countries
arrived in Argentina yesterday to help hunt for the bombers of a Jewish
community centre in Buenos Aires. The blast, on Monday, killed 27 people.
</TEXT>
