<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JUL 94 / Clinton hints at flexibility on healthcare bill
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JEREMY KAHN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
President Bill Clinton yesterday emphasised his flexibility over healthcare
legislation at a conference of state governors in an effort to keep the
reform on track.
Speaking in Boston, Massachusetts, Mr Clinton said he would accept any plan
that guaranteed 'universal coverage' for all US citizens. He seemed to
indicate still further flexibility when he later said he would not veto a
reform bill that 'moved toward universal coverage'.
'I have no pride of authorship and no pride of details, I just want to find
a solution that works,' Mr Clinton said in his speech.
However, in an earlier speech at the conference, Mr Robert Dole, the Senate
Republican leader and chief opponent of Mr Clinton's healthcare initiative,
accused the president of blocking a compromise. He said Mr Clinton was
'ratcheting up the rhetoric' and fomenting 'class warfare' with statements
about the increasing healthcare burden on the middle class that would ensue
if universal coverage was not achieved.
Both the president and Mr Dole urged one another to deflate the rhetoric
surrounding the healthcare reform debate which is beginning to draw to a
conclusion in Congress and said they were willing to compromise.
Mr Dole said: 'I think the seeds of a bipartisan bill still exist if the
administration is willing to come our way.'
Mr Dole promoted the insurance reform proposal he has floated as an
alternative to Mr Clinton's demand for an overhaul of the healthcare system
and coverage for every American. But Mr Clinton said he was highly sceptical
of the plan, which would allow workers to keep the same insurance policy
even if they switched jobs but would not mandate that employers pay for it.
Mr Clinton said there was evidence that insurance reform without universal
coverage was not a workable solution because it resulted in higher cost for
most workers.
