<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JUL 94 / Brussels to probe pay-TV venture
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The European Commission has ordered an investigation into a planned joint
venture by two German media groups and the state telephone monopoly. It is
suspicious that the concentration could create a dominant position in the
German market for pay-television services.
Bertelsmann, the world's second largest media group, Kirch, one of Germany's
biggest private television companies, and Deutsche Telekom notified Brussels
of their plans last month. They intend setting up a company to provide
infrastructure, marketing and booking services for commercial pay-TV,
including such services as video-on-demand, home banking and interactive
television. The company would be known as MSG Media Service.
The Commission is concerned that, with the introduction of digital
broadcasting in Germany over the next few years, the pay-TV market will
expand rapidly. This is particularly so in Germany where a large number of
households already receive cable or satellite television.
'The proposed concentration raises the question whether MSG could obtain, on
a permanent basis, a dominant position on the German market for technical
and administrative services for Pay-TV,' the Commission said yesterday.
Deutsche Telekom is the country's leading cable network operator. It also
recently acquired a substantial stake in the European satellite operator
Ses-Astra.
Bertelsmann and Kirch have a stake in Premiere, Germany's only pay-TV
channel, and Kirch is a dominant programme supplier to German television.
Media analysts value its library at more than Dollars 2bn.
'It is therefore particularly important to examine the effects which may
result from the combination of companies which probably would have a leading
position in pay-TV and cable networks in the future,' the Commission said.
Brussels is particularly uneasy that, by dominating the pay-TV
infrastructure at an early stage, the joint venture would control standards
for any newcomers. It fears MSG would be able to set the standards for
household decoders.
Mr John Scaife, a media financier at London-based Charon Capital, said: 'The
concern is that if the joint venture effectively controls the gateway to pay
television services, and people at home do not want to have to pay for more
than one decoder, then this group could be in a very dominant position.
Anyone coming in later, would have to use their standards.'
The Commission decided the need for investigation went beyond Germany's
borders arguing that the proposed concentration could affect the access of
pay-TV suppliers from other EU member states to the German market. It has
four months to decide on the merger.
</TEXT>
