FT  20 JUL 94 / Nato and WEU remain apart
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRUCE CLARK
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Co-ordination between Nato and the Western European Union over how to
organise joint military task forces has failed to get off the ground, a
senior Nato officer disclosed yesterday. A new relationship between Nato and
the WEU was proclaimed after January's Nato summit, at which the US appeared
to give its blessing to the idea of western Europe taking more
responsibility for its own defence. But a speech yesterday by Air Vice
Marshal John Cheshire, until recently an assistant chief of staff at Nato's
military headquarters, indicated virtually no progress on linking the two
institutions had been made. He told the Royal United Services Institute the
WEU's permanent staff had declined to enter discussions about how to
organise task forces, on the grounds they had no mandate to do so from
member governments.
