FT  20 JUL 94 / German pay experiment
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BONN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Germany is to experiment with performance-related pay and bonuses for civil
servants to make its bureaucracy more efficient. Bonn, which has often
complained that cumbersome bureaucracy hampers economic growth, approved a
small shake-up in the cash-strapped public sector, provided there is no
increase in overall costs. 'Existing pay structures in the public service
apparently do not always make it sufficiently clear that performance is the
key criterion for paying public service staff,' said an interior ministry
report approved by cabinet. 'For work which is considerably above average,
public servants could receive a performance bonus as a once-off payment or
for a limited period.' Meanwhile, Volkswagen, the German carmaker, said it
had agreed a pay deal giving workers a 1 per cent rise plus extra payments
totalling DM900 (Pounds 370).
