   By CHRISTOPHER BOBINSKI
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WARSAW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Polish government is to retain control of the country's pipeline and
rail petrol distribution system under cautious new privatisation plans
announced yesterday. CPN, the state-owned service station operator, which
owns 3,300 outlets, will be split into three and passed over to refining
companies whose shares would then be offered to domestic and foreign
investors, the government said. The state would retain golden shares in the
companies with veto powers over the closure of refineries. The Poles will
also seek to delay the lifting of quotas on petroleum imports from the
European Union, promised for the spring of 1997. At present 20 per cent of
Poland's petrol is imported.
