FT  20 JUL 94 / Sweden plans tighter budget
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER BROWN-HUMES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   STOCKHOLM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Swedish government will have to intensify its savings drive if it is to
meet its debt stabilisation targets, Mr Carl Bildt, prime minister, warned
yesterday. He said new measures would have to be outlined in next January's
budget if state debt as a proportion of gross national product was to be
stabilised by 1998. Although he was not specific, commentators say that up
to SKr30bn (Pounds 2.5bn) of extra budget-strengthening measures may be
needed to regain market confidence. The government has already promised
budget savings of SKr100bn over the next five years. The shaky state of
public finances has become the focus of heated political debate in the
run-up to September's general election. This follows the decision by
Skandia, the leading Swedish insurer, to boycott government bonds in protest
at Sweden's budget deficit and fast-rising debt.
