FT  20 JUL 94 / Bosnian Serbs silent on vote
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURA SILBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BELGRADE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Bosnian Serb leaders yesterday ended two days of heated debate, refusing to
reveal their decision on a 'last chance' international peace plan. But they
reportedly voted for conditional acceptance, an answer previously dismissed
as unacceptable by the plan's architects: the US, Russia, Germany, France
and Britain. The conditions are to be submitted to the western 'contact
group' in Geneva today, and are believed to include constitutional
guarantees allowing the self-proclaimed Serb state to join Serbia instead of
remaining in the planned Bosnian union with the Moslem-Croat federation.
They also sought revision of the 'take it or leave it' maps to include the
division of Sarajevo and access to the Adriatic sea. The contact group had
set a Tuesday deadline for the warring parties to give either a clear Yes or
No. Bosnia's Moslems have indicated they will accept the plan.
