<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JUL 94 / Turkey-Russia debt deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MURRAY BROWN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ISTANBUL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Turkey and Russia agreed terms yesterday to settle a Dollars 480m (Pounds
308m) debt under which Ankara will be repaid in cash and barter over the
next two years. The debt represents credit lines provided by Turkey's Export
Import Bank to finance Russia's imports of Turkish goods and construction
services, on the back of a 1984 natural gas protocol, under which Turkey
takes delivery of Russian gas in exchange for supply of goods and services.
The agreement envisages Turkey will be repaid Dollars 90m in cash by the end
of September and a further Dollars 100m before the end of 1996. In addition,
it will take goods worth Dollars 100m in 1994, and the balance of goods over
the next two years.
