<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JUL 94 / Berlusconi backs down over curbs on powers of arrest
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Silvio Berlusconi, the Italian prime minister, suffered his first serious
reverse yesterday when he was forced to redraft controversial legislation
restricting the judiciary's powers of arrest.
The legislation, approved in cabinet last Thursday as a decree, split
Italy's rightwing coalition and threatened to bring down the two-month-old
government.
The decree will now be formally blocked in parliament and the government
will introduce new legislation in the form of a draft law. It will address
the most criticised aspects of the decree that provoked the resignations
last week of the Milan anti-corruption magistrates responsible for exposing
the corrupt practices of Italy's political and business elite.
Mr Umberto Bossi, leader of the populist Northern League and one of the main
critics of the decree, said yesterday he had no wish to bring down the
government. However, he has taken advantage of Mr Berlusconi's difficulties
to undermine the prime minister's authority.
Yesterday Mr Bossi is reported to have blocked plans by Mr Berlusconi to
make a nationwide televised address on the issue. Mr Bossi, in Strasbourg
for the European parliament, co-ordinated his position with Mr Gianfranco
Fini, leader of the neo-fascist MSI/National Alliance.
These partners in the coalition, who have both campaigned hard against
corruption, became increasingly critical of the decree as the public outcry
grew.
The compromise was patched up after 24 hours of hectic and angry exchanges
between the coalition partners. The decree, which had immediate effect, will
be superseded by a draft bill whose text can be amended during its course
through parliament.
The draft will restore the discretionary powers of magistrates to use
preventive detention in cases of bribery, corruption and extortion that
involve the public administration. These cover many of the cases in the
anti-corruption drive of the past two and a half years that has changed the
political face of Italy.
It was the exclusion of these cases from preventive detention that caused
much of the public outcry and allowed nearly 1,800 people to be released
from jail. Of these, only 167 had been held on corruption charges. The
government did not clarify whether those just released would be obliged to
go back to jail. But the new law will not be passed by parliament, probably
until mid-August.
The new draft allows magistrates to retain the secrecy of their
investigations of persons suspected of belonging to the mafia to beyond
three months. The decree obliged magistrates to inform anyone immediately
they were the subject of investigations. Proposed restrictions on the press
have also been lifted.
Berlusconi own-goal, Page 2
Bonds, Page 29
Currencies, Page 31
World stocks, Page 37
</TEXT>
