<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JUL 94 / Lara wins record-breaking Pounds 500,000 sponsorship deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mercury Asset Management, the UK's largest fund management company, has
signed up West Indies cricketer Brian Lara, the world record-holding
batsman, in the largest ever individual cricket sponsorship deal valued at
Pounds 500,000.
Mr Lara was uncustomarily kitted out yesterday in pin-stripe suit and bowler
hat to open MAM's first innings in sports sponsorship, long an avenue of
corporate image-promotion for financial services companies.
MAM, which had done almost no advertising until two years ago, launched a
print campaign earlier this year, featuring dramatic sports imagery.
The company, which has grown to manage Pounds 60bn in assets, has recently
shifted its marketing efforts to its retail businesses including unit and
investment trusts tailored for wealthy private clients as well as personal
pensions business.
'The corporate theme is one of sporting excellence,' explained Mr Richard
Royds, managing director of Mercury Fund Managers. Although it was Mr Lara's
agent who made the initial approach to MAM, Mr Royds said his company's
market research suggested it would gain the greatest impact on its target
audience by sponsoring either cricket or rugby.
Sponsoring Mr Lara appealed to MAM, Mr Royds said, because 'he is the most
prolific run scorer in the world. We are the leading investment management
company in the UK. The tie-up is obvious'.
In April, Mr Lara broke the world record for the highest score in a Test
innings when he made 375 against England. Then, last month, he hit a world
record for a first-class innings, 501 for Warwickshire against Durham. He is
the first to hold both world records since Sir Donald Bradman, widely
regarded as the greatest batsman of all time, in the 1930s.
Mr Lara will invest his sign-on fee in Mercury's flagship unit trust, The
Mercury Portfolio. The contract with MAM will run until the end of 1996. A
performance-related element could raise the total above the basic Pounds
500,000.
In return for the sponsorship, Mr Lara will appear in MAM advertising and
appear at some MAM-sponsored charity events, while his cricket clothing will
carry some MAM advertising.
MAM, which is 75 per cent owned by SG Warburg, is hardly Mr Lara's sole
corporate sponsor. His others include a mobile telephone company based in
south-west England, Joe Bloggs clothing, and BWIA, the West Indies airline
which has given Mr Lara 375,000 free air miles.
In recent weeks, Mr Lara has been plagued by press reports of excessive
lateness for games and, in one well-publicised incident, for producing a
mobile telephone while fielding.
His contract contains a 'let-out' clause if he engages in certain specified
types of conduct. 'I'm not going to tell you what those are,' Mr Royds said.
</TEXT>
