<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JUL 94 / UK Company News: Legal and General's new business decline
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Legal &amp; General, the investment management and financial services group, saw
the value of its worldwide new business fall from Pounds 156.1m to Pounds
146.3m in the first half of 1994.
The group, which calculates the figures by adding 10 per cent of single
premiums to annual premium income, said UK life and pensions premiums fell
from Pounds 102.3m to Pounds 122.7m in the first half.
Although UK annual premiums also fell, the downturn was offset by Pounds
74.7m (Pounds 54m) generated by its unit trust operations and Pounds 44m
(Pounds 33.4m) from overseas businesses.
Mr David Prosser, group chief executive, said: 'The current UK market for
our products has proved difficult and this has been reflected in our new
business figures.'
The group's direct salesforce has been cut from 2,400 to 1,900 to improve
efficiency, but Mr Prosser warned that the operating environment was
unlikely to improve in the short term.
</TEXT>
