FT  20 JUL 94 / Europarliament elects president
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   STRASBOURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
German Socialist Mr Klaus Haensch was elected president of the European
parliament yesterday. Mr Haensch, who won 365 votes in the 567-member
assembly, succeeds fellow German Mr Egon Klepsch. He will hold the post for
half the five-year legislature. Mr Haensch's only opponent was French
Liberal MEP Mr Yves Galland who gained 87 votes. Mr Haensch, 55, has been an
MEP since the first direct elections to the assembly in 1979 and has
concentrated on foreign and security policy matters. He has said his
priorities are to secure increased powers for the parliament in the planned
1996 review of the EU's workings and to make full use of new powers it
secured under the Maastricht treaty.
