<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JUL 94 / Turkey-Russia debt accord
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MURRAY BROWN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ISTANBUL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Turkey and Russia agreed terms yesterday to settle a Dollars 480m debt under
which Ankara will be repaid in cash and barter over the next two years. The
deal was signed in Ankara at the end of a two-day visit by Russia's first
deputy prime minister, Mr Oleg Soskovets. The debt represents credit lines
provided by Turkey's Export Import Bank to finance Russia's imports of
Turkish goods and construction services, on the back of a 1984 natural gas
protocol, under which Turkey takes delivery of Russian gas in exchange for
supply of goods and services.
The agreement envisages Turkey will be repaid Dollars 90m in cash by the end
of September and a further Dollars 100m before the end of 1996. In addition,
it will take goods worth Dollars 100m in 1994, and the balance of goods over
the next two years. Turkey is understood to be considering taking
Russian-made MI-24 Hind-D combat helicopters to bolster its war effort
against Kurdish rebels. Under the gas protocol, Turkey currently receives
6bn cubic metres of gas a year for household and industrial use. It has
agreed to take an additional 2.5bn cubic metres from 1997.
</TEXT>
