<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JUL 94 / Bosnian Serbs keep peace verdict secret: Decision believed
to be a notional 'yes' with conditions attached
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURA SILBER and AP
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BELGRADE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Bosnian Serbs, in a deft move that will exasperate international peace
brokers, yesterday reached a verdict on a peace plan for the republic but
resolved to keep it secret.
The decision, contained in a sealed envelope which will be delivered to the
five-nation 'contact group' on Bosnia in Geneva, was believed to amount to a
notional 'yes' with up to six conditions attached.
The contact group - made up of the US, Russia, Britain, France and Germany -
has told Bosnia's warring parties to expect an escalating series of punitive
measures unless they agree to a plan which splits the republic 51-49 between
the Moslems and Croats on one hand and Serbs on the other.
Mr Miroslav Toholj, the Bosnian Serb Information Minister, emerged from a
two-day debate in the Serb stronghold of Pale with the sealed message and
said: 'The Bosnian Serb parliament yesterday and today has adopted a
decision which is in this envelope and which will be submitted to the
contact group.'
Earlier Mr Radovan Karadzic, the Bosnian Serb leader, indicated that the
assembly was likely to endorse a conditional approval. 'We have reached no
decision but I hope we can accept it in some way.'
The conditions were believed to include:
guarantees that the Bosnian Serb state would have full independence from the
Moslem-Croat federation and would enjoy the right to join up with Serbia
proper;
access to the Adriatic for the Serb entity;
a new partition of Sarajevo.
During their emotional, closed-door debate, Serb deputies are reported to
have railed bitterly against a plan which they described as a international
diktat.
guaranteed lifting of sanctions on both Serbia and Montenegro;
By voicing conditional approval, the Serbs appeared to be hoping to weaken
the resolve of the contact group to impose punitive measures, and possibly
divide the group down the middle.
Russia, a traditional friend of the Serbs, will now be able to argue that
its proteges are being relatively co-operative and should not be punished
any further.
Serb officials said that if the international community insisted on a
straight yes or no, the existing peace plan would have to be put to a
referendum which would almost certainly deliver a rejection.
AP adds: The chief prosecutor of the UN war crimes tribunal for the Balkans
said yesterday he expected indictments against suspects from the former
Yugoslavia by the end of the year.
Prosecutor Richard Goldstone of South Africa also told a news conference
that he hoped the tribunal would be a first step in setting up an
international court to prosecute crimes against humanity.
The tribunal was set up in The Hague in February 1993 to investigate
hundreds of alleged war crimes committed in Croatia and Bosnia-Hercegovina.
It is the first of its kind since the 1945 Nuremberg trials of Nazi war
criminals.
'If this tribunal is effective, it must act quickly,' said Mr Goldstone.
'Already too much time has elapsed. I will consider myself to have failed if
indictments are not brought before the end of the year.'
</TEXT>
