<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JUL 94 / Berlusconi forced to retreat over judiciary decree:
Legislation withdrawn after split in Italian coalition
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Silvio Berlusconi, the Italian prime minister, suffered his first serious
reverse yesterday when he was forced to redraft legislation restricting the
judiciary's powers of arrest.
The legislation, approved in cabinet last Thursday as a decree, split
Italy's right-wing coalition and threatened to bring down the two month-old
government.
The decree will now be formally blocked in parliament and the government
will introduce new legislation. This will be in the form of a draft law that
addresses the most criticised aspects of the decree that provoked last week
the resignations of the Milan anti-corruption magistrates responsible for
exposing the corrupt practices of Italy's political and business elite.
'A crisis of the government at this stage would have caused serious damage
to the country, especially when important economic decision have to be
taken,' said Mr Giuliano Ferrara, the minister for relations with
parliament.
The lira weakened during the day, falling to L1,006 against the D-mark, but
recovered slightly on the news of the deal between Mr Berlusconi and his
rebel coalition partners.
Mr Umberto Bossi, leader of the populist Northern League and one of the main
critics of the decree, said yesterday he had no wish to bring down the
government. However, Mr Bossi has taken advantage of Mr Berlusconi's
difficulties to undermine the prime minister's authority.
Yesterday Mr Bossi reportedly blocked plans by Mr Berlusconi to make a
nationwide televised address on the issue. Mr Bossi, who was in Strasbourg
for the European parliament, co-ordinated his position with Mr Gianfranco
Fini, the leader of the neo-fascist MSI/National Alliance.
These two partners in the coalition, who have both campaigned hard against
corruption, became increasingly critical of the decree as the public outcry
grew.
The draft will restore the discretionary powers of magistrates to use
preventive detention in cases of bribery, corruption and extortion that
involve the public administration.
It was the exclusion of these cases from preventive detention that caused
much of the public outcry and allowed nearly 1,800 people to be released
from jail. Of these, only 167 had been held on corruption charges.
The government did not clarify whether those just released would be obliged
to go back to jail. But the new law will not probably be passed by
parliament until mid-August.
The new draft allows magistrates to keep secret beyond three months their
investigations of persons suspected of belonging to the mafia. The decree
obliged magistrates to inform anyone immediately they were the subject of
investigations.
Restrictions have also been lifted on the press, which the decree forbid
from publishing details of the names of those under investigation -
restrictions that were ignored anyway.
But Mr Berlusconi insisted the broad lines of the decree would be retained
and he reaffirmed the need to prevent people's basic freedoms being abused
by over-zealous use of arrest and imprisonment.
Berlusconi weakened by an own-goal, Page 2
</TEXT>
