<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JUL 94 / London Stock Exchange: DIY worries
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER JOHN, CHRISTOPHER PRICE and JOEL KIBAZO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Stocks with home improvement interests weakened in response to reports of
expansion plans by US DIY group Home Depot. Ladbroke, owner of the Texas
chain, slipped 3 to 175p, B&amp;Q parent Kingfisher declined 7 to 527p and Do It
All co-owner Boots fell 11 to 538p. Boots partner WH Smith was the one
bright spot, managing a rise of 5 to 481p.
However, stores specialists were mostly sceptical over the US group's impact
on the UK market. One said that Home Depot was aware of the difficult
trading environment in UK DIY and would more likely be targeting the German
and French markets as the focus of its European strategy. In addition, the
US company favours large store formats, which could run into planning
difficulties in the UK.
Boots was further undermined by weekend press reports that a consortium of
institutions was considering bidding for the company's drugs division. The
suggestion was met with general incredulity by analysts, who pointed out
that the offshoot was most likely to be bought by a kindred business, and
who also expressed surprise that the originally mooted price of Pounds 1bn
had apparently dropped to between Pounds 600m to Pounds 700m, according to
the reports.
Media conglomerate Pearson strengthened 22 to 660p, making a gain of almost
Pounds 1 a share over the past two weeks. Recent underperformance has been
redressed by a spate of buy recommendations and optimism that the
conglomerate will have a significant voice in the new Channel Five
television station.
Wm Low delivered J. Sainsbury the information requested by the country's
biggest supermarket group - a move which could trigger the anticipated
contest for the Scottish company following the friendly Pounds 154m bid from
Tesco last week. Sainsbury's mulling gave the sector a chance to pause for
breath after last week's heightened activity, with Low's shares adding just
3 at 256p, Tesco gaining 5 1/2 at 238 1/2 p and Sainsbury edging forward a
half-penny to 397 1/2 p.
Strong half-time results from Coca-Cola and the continuing hot weather
helped Cadbury Schweppes rise 7 1/2 to 451 1/2 p. Sugar processor Tate &amp;
Lyle firmed 5 to 415p. Unilever eased 5 to 1005p as the soap wars saga with
arch-rival Procter &amp; Gamble rumbled on.
Buying of Wellcome, ahead of Thursday's interim results, was boosted by a
revival of speculation that the company was a takeover or merger target. The
company is changing its year-end and reporting figures for the four months
to the end of June. The shares put on 13 at 629p. Elsewhere in the sector,
SmithKline Beecham, which reports full-year figures today, fell 6 to 394p on
profit-taking.
High street lending banks Barclays and Lloyds were pulled in different
directions on switch advice from one securities house. Barclays was off 5 at
one stage after Lehman Brothers downgraded the stock from buy to hold.
However, the shares picked up with the market to close a penny ahead at
555p. Meanwhile, Lehman upgraded Lloyds on the expectation that it will
successfully merge with the Cheltenham &amp; Gloucester Building Society and
boost its earnings by 12 per cent in the first year. Also, SGST reiterated
its buy stance on Lloyds and the shares rose 9 to 566p.
Several stocks with hotel interests benefited from recent news on the
improving trading outlook. Forte gained 8 1/2 at 230p, Stakis 2 1/2 at 88p,
Bass 10 at 555p, and Whitbread 12 at 553p ahead of its agm statement today.
Engineering group Wagon Industrial closed a penny firmer at 500p as NatWest
Securities said its rating remained undemanding, although the sticking point
was the yield.
A stock overhang, together with general profit-taking, left shares in GKN
trailing 11 at 609p. It was also profit-taking that weakened Siebe, which
closed 9 down at 598p after trade of 1.8m. A two-way pull in FKI brought
volume of 3.2m as the shares closed unchanged at 180p, after the group
announced disposals of Pounds 46m. One market watcher said: 'This is a good
deal as it reduces debt and enables it to pursue its acquisition policy.'
Negative weekend press comment left conglomerate Tomkins 3 off at 221p.
Confirmation from dry cleaning company Sketchley that one of its two
executive deputy chairmen is to leave the company cast a shadow over the
stock. The shares eased 5 to 105p.
</TEXT>
