<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JUL 94 / World Stock Markets (America): Mainly muted response to
company news
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US equities improved slightly yesterday in a quiet session highlighted by a
fresh batch of corporate results, writes Frank McGurty in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average finished 1.62 higher at 3,755.43, while the
more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 was 1.06 firmer at 455.22. In the
secondary markets, the American SE composite was 1.04 ahead at 432.59 and
the Nasdaq composite added 1.26 at 722.62. Trading volume on the New York SE
amounted to 227m shares.
The opening was weak, following a pattern which is typical of Monday
mornings which follow 'double witching' rallies. Yesterday, the Dow tumbled
about 15 points in the first minutes of activity, wiping out most of the
expiration-related gains struck in the final minutes of trading last week.
Apart from the technical considerations, the restrained tone reflected
anticipation of tomorrow's semi-annual Humphrey-Hawkins testimony by Mr Alan
Greenspan. The Federal Reserve Board chief will brief a Senate committee on
the state of the economy, and investors were hoping for hints on the timing
of the next move to raise interest rates.
As the day progressed, market indices managed to climb off the session's
lows, pushing into positive territory by mid-afternoon. An absence of fresh
economic news, and benign trends on the bond and currency markets, provided
an uncluttered vantage point from which to scrutinise the second-quarter
performances of several market bellwethers.
For better or worse, the reaction to the results was generally muted. Chase
Manhattan posted net income of Dollars 307m in the second three months of
1994, well ahead of its 1993 result of Dollars 233m, but the stock finished
unchanged at Dollars 38 3/4 .
Nationsbank also beat the forecasts of analysts, publishing a 42 per cent
improvement in earnings, but its share price nudged only Dollars 5/8 ahead
to Dollars 55 1/8 .
In pharmaceuticals, Upjohn issued a strong earnings report but the reaction
of investors was tepid. The stock added Dollars  1/2 at Dollars 30 1/2 .
US West, near the top of the NYSE's most active list, dropped Dollars 1 1/2
to Dollars 40 3/8 in volume of 2.8m shares. The regional telephone group's
earnings showed no improvement from the previous year, but the downturn in
its share price was more a reflection of a decision to purchase two Atlanta
cable television operations and a downgrading by Goldman Sachs.
On the Nasdaq, Microsoft was marked up Dollars 1 7/8 to Dollars 50 1/2 after
settling a four-year federal antitrust lawsuit. Analysts played down the
impact of the agreement on the company's domination of the computer software
industry.
Synergen plunged Dollars 4 3/8 , or nearly 50 per cent, to Dollars 4 1/2
after announcing that its leading drug prospect had performed poorly in
recent clinical trials.
Canada
The Toronto market was also a shade higher following a session of low
turnover.
The TSE 300 composite index added 6.4 at 4,199.8 after spending most of the
day little changed from Friday's closing level. Advances outnumbered
declines by 369 to 342 after volume of 33.9m shares, well below Friday's
53.2m. Trading value was CDollars 276.4m.
The 14 stock groups were evenly divided between winners and losers. Real
estate recorded the day's biggest change, rising 1.85 per cent. Industrial
products and mining gained 1.15 and 1.07 per cent.
</TEXT>
