<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JUL 94 / Letters to the Editor: Cultural trends in German equity
markets
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr JIM PLATTS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, On July 14 I attended a manufacturing engineering conference where
discussion centred on the competitiveness of European industry. We
consistently heard examples both from the speakers and from the floor of
long-term views and solid investment in Germany (and elsewhere) and the lack
of such investment and vision in the UK.
It was typical that on the same day I should find a report in the FT, by
David Waller, on the lack of a share culture in Germany, as if it were some
kind of disability ('Resisting the bait of equity ownership'). I think what
he meant was that they don't have a share trading culture - because they
recognise that wealth creation is a product of custodianship in which share
trading can only ever be secondary.
Do we get a balancing article on the lack of an ownership culture in the UK?
Jim Platts,
department of engineering,
