FT  19 JUL 94 / Letters to the Editor: House price trends and recovery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr PETER MILLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Samuel Brittan is right to point out that soaring house prices are
unhealthy for the economy (Economic Viewpoint, July 7). But he fails to
comment on the problems caused by a depressed housing market.
Without a strong housing market - remembering that the phrase refers as much
to the number of transactions as to prices - the economy cannot reap the
benefits of the increased outlay on goods and services that go with moving
house.
The 'wealth effects' that a modest rise in residential property prices
create cannot be measured, but without their reassuring presence to the
home-owner, consumer spending is unlikely to play a large role in
facilitating the economic recovery.
Peter Miller,
Royal Institution of Chartered Surveyors,
12 Great George Street,
Parliament Square,
London,
SW1P 3AD
