<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JUL 94 / Dorrell promise on M-way charging
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEWART DALBY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Stephen Dorrell, chief secretary to the Treasury, yesterday told the
Commons transport committee that the government intended to proceed with
direct charging for motorway use, probably through electronic pricing.
He could not, however, put a date on when charging would be introduced or
how much it could be expected to raise.
He said the charges would be in addition to existing taxes. The hope was
that the money would be ring-fenced and spent on motorways.
A green paper issued by Mr John MacGregor, the transport secretary, earlier
this year said that direct charging for motorways could raise Pounds 11bn a
year but this would depend on the level of tariffs.
Mr Ian Wilson, a Treasury official, said transport taxes raised Pounds
22.4bn a year, far more than was spent on motorways, but it went into an
integrated budget.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9621 Regulation, Administration of Transportation.
    P4785 Inspection and Fixed Facilities.
</IN>
<XX>
