<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JUL 94 / Asda refund pledge steps up price war
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Asda, the UK's fourth-largest grocery retailer, is stepping up the
supermarket price war with a promise to refund the difference on a basket of
goods if customers can buy the same goods more cheaply elsewhere.
The store chain said its guarantee did not mean it would refund the price of
individual goods but it would make up the difference if customers found they
could purchase their weekly shopping for less at a rival store.
The move will put further pressure on profit margins in the grocery market,
which has seen a huge expansion in selling space and the rapid growth of a
new breed of cut-price discount stores. It comes as the UK's three largest
groups - J Sainsbury, Tesco, and Argyll, owner of Safeway - were predicting
that margins would stabilise after falling since last autumn.
