<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JUL 94 / Westminster plan could end 'eyesore'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEWART DALBY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Plans to relocate 3,000 civil servants from the central London headquarters
of the Departments of Environment and Transport - and transform the
Westminster skyline in the process - were put forward yesterday.
Sir George Young, housing minister, announced that an outline planning
application to demolish three 21-storey tower blocks in Marsham Street had
been made.
The application to Westminster city council for a development of offices,
shops, houses and parking spaces was made through Property Holdings, a
government agency. Demolition will not take place until at least 1997.
Mr Michael Heseltine, then environment secretary, announced two years ago
that the building, whose three towers loom above the Houses of Parliament,
was so badly designed that demolition was the only solution. Marsham Street
has been described as the ugliest building in London.
It was suggested at that time that the workers at the Ministry of
Environment and Ministry of Transport would move to new offices in
Docklands. It now seems that they will be relocated to other sites in
Westminster.
Sir George Young said yesterday that the maximum height of any new buildings
would be half that of the existing buildings.
He said: 'The magnificent silhouette of the Houses of Parliament will be
restored.'
The outline planning application envisages 690,000 sq ft of offices, 175,000
sq ft of houses and 30,000 sq ft of shops and restaurants.
The site is valued at between Pounds 20m and Pounds 30m, but it is not clear
whether the government will develop it or sell it to private developers.
Sir George said: 'The government will be staying on the site for another two
years and will then take a judgment as to whether it needs the site. If so,
we will develop it ourselves, if not, we will dispose of it on the open
market at the time.'
</TEXT>
