FT  19 JUL 94 / Tory MPs urge limit on postal sell-off
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Conservative backbenchers who are opposed to the privatisation of the Post
Office yesterday put forward a parliamentary early day motion opposing the
sale of a majority shareholding, Roland Rudd writes.
The move is an indication of the determination of some Conservative MPs to
ensure that the corporation remains in the public sector with more
commercial freedom.
The motion, which has attracted all-party support, welcomes the recognition
that the Post Office needs more commercial freedom but says it can be
achieved without full privatisation.
Mr Jim Lester, Tory MP for Broxtowe in Nottinghamshire, said: 'I cannot see
the economic case for selling off more than half the shares in the Post
Office when it can have commercial freedom within the public sector.' Sir
David Knox, Tory MP for Staffordshire Morelands, said the 'postal delivery
service should continue to be protected by the state'.
The government's preferred option is to sell 51 per cent of the shares in
the Royal Mail and Parcelforce. Tory MPs opposed to this would compromise on
a flotation of between 30 per cent and 49 per cent.
