<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JUL 94 / Move to start cable TV in Ulster
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Independent Television Commission plans to try again to bring cable
television to Northern Ireland, more than 10 years after the first
experimental licence was awarded.
The ITC is expected to advertise a licence or licences in the autumn and has
not ruled out the possibility of advertising a single licence covering all
of Northern Ireland - and not just Belfast and its surrounding area.
If a single licence is advertised covering the more than 500,000 homes in
the province it would be one of the largest cable television franchises in
the UK - on a par with franchises such as the west Midlands.
A cable franchise for the Belfast area was one of the first 11 experimental
franchises to be offered in 1983 but the consortium, including British
Telecom, STC and Ulster Television, did not make any progress. The lack of
movement led to the licences being revoked in 1991.
In March Mr Desmond Smyth, chief executive of Ulster Television, said he
believed the time was now right for cable in Northern Ireland and admitted
the company was in preliminary talks with Mercury Communications.
Mr Jon Davey, director of cable at the ITC, said yesterday: 'I don't think
cable is out of the woods yet but the environment is very different from
even three years ago.' Unlike the franchises awarded by the old Cable
Authority, the new 'local delivery franchises' go to the highest bidder.
The signs are that there will be more than one potential operator interested
in Northern Ireland, one of the largest uncabled areas of the UK and a
region where there is a high interest in television choice and, almost
certainly, in competing telecommunications services.
The ITC has already advertised this year four of the new local franchises -
the latest last Friday for southern East Anglia covering Thetford, Diss,
Bury St Edmunds, Sudbury, Clacton and surrounding areas. This involves about
250,000 homes.
The first of the new franchises, which allow over-the-air broadcast of
channels using microwave frequencies as well as cable, attracted the
surprisingly high annual bid of Pounds 1.6m when advertised in west Kent.
The franchise went to Eurobell, a cable operator with franchises in the
Crawley area of West Sussex and in Devon.
The new franchise areas often include semi-rural areas that are of interest
to cable operators in nearby large cities.
Last month the ITC announced that Cable Communications Fylde and Wyre had
won the new licence for Blackpool and Fylde with a cash bid of Pounds
762,000. The ITC also advertised a licence covering Chesterfield, Bolsover,
Matlock, Belper and the surrounding area.
Cable television is now available to about 3m homes in the UK with more than
650,000 of them subscribing to modern networks increasingly offering
telephone services as well as television channels.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P4841 Cable and Other Pay Television Services.
    P9651 Regulation of Miscellaneous Commercial Sectors.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
