<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JUL 94 / Treasury on course for PSBR target
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government's budget deficit fell to a lower than expected Pounds 2.86bn
in June from Pounds 4.3bn in May. This indicates that the Treasury is well
on course to achieve its recently set target of Pounds 36.1bn for the public
sector borrowing requirement in the financial year to the end of March 1995.
The Treasury and the Central Statistical Office reported yesterday that the
PSBR fell to Pounds 11.4bn in the three months to the end of June from
Pounds 13.4bn in the first three months of the 1993-94 financial year.
Excluding last month's privatisation proceeds of Pounds 180m from the sale
of Northern Ireland Electricity shares, the PSBR in June was Pounds 3.04bn.
Without privatisation income the deficit shrank by Pounds 3bn to Pounds
11.9bn in the three months to the end of June from Pounds 14.9bn in the same
period last year.
The June deficit was markedly lower than the City's Pounds 3.7bn consensus
forecast. The Treasury said early tax payments by the self-employed ahead of
a July 1 deadline boosted government revenues. Income tax receipts jumped to
Pounds 5.53bn in June from Pounds 4.18bn in May and Pounds 4.8bn in June
last year.
The overall improvement in the government's finances so far this year
reflects relatively strong revenue growth and only a small rise in
government outlays.
Cash receipts were Pounds 17.1bn in June and Pounds 50.5bn in the first
three months of 1994-95 to show a 4.3 per cent rise compared with Pounds
48.4bn in the same period last year.
Cash outlays were Pounds 20.6bn in June and Pounds 62.4bn in the first three
months of the financial year, up 1.6 per cent on spending of Pounds 61.4bn
in the equivalent period of 1993-94. These were boosted, however, by higher
interest payments and lower privatisation proceeds, which count as negative
expenditure. Net departmental outlays in the three months fell 1.5 per cent
compared with a year ago to Pounds 58.9bn.
Yesterday's figures had no impact on financial markets but economists were
impressed. Mr Michael Saunders, UK economist for Salomon Brothers
International, said that the scale of improvement in the fiscal deficit was
likely to be sustained over the rest of 1994-1995. 'Assuming that the
November Budget does not shift the fiscal stance, the PSBR could be down to
Pounds 25bn or 3.5 per cent of GDP in 1995-96' compared with Pounds 45.9bn
in 1993-94, he said. This would be 'among the smallest deficits in the
European Union'.
</TEXT>
