<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JUL 94 / Scotland faces new charity rules
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Pressure to extend some controls on English charities to Scotland will be
generated by the report tomorrow of a Department of Trade and Industry
taskforce set up as part of the government's deregulation exercise.
The taskforce has been seeking ways to reduce accounting, fundraising,
trading and other burdens on charitable activities and its report will make
a number of recommendations in these areas. But as far as Scotland is
concerned, it will have the effect of arguing for more regulation.
In Scotland the charitable sector is less strongly policed than in England
and Wales. There is no Scottish equivalent of the Charity Commissioners and
the 1992 Charities Act, designed to tighten up on potential abuse, does not
apply there.
This has given rise to concerns that enforcement of the act in England and
Wales is likely to encourage a growth in dubious fundraising and other
abuses north of the border.
The taskforce report is likely to accept the case mounted by the Scottish
Council of Voluntary Organisations that there should be common standards
throughout the UK, governing issues such as the regulation of fundraising
and the role of charity trustees.
More than a third of nearly 200 recommendations in the report have been
accepted by the government, and further studies will be commissioned in some
other areas.
Voluntary sector representatives told the taskforce that one of the most
effective ways of reducing tax burdens on charities would be freeing them
from value added tax on their activities, but this is unlikely to be agreed
by the government.
</TEXT>
