<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JUL 94 / Squeeze put on eligibility for council housing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government yesterday unveiled plans to tighten the rules by which the
homeless can apply for local authority housing, triggering a furious protest
from opposition parties and independent pressure groups.
The plans, announced in the Commons by Sir George Young, the housing
minister, will mean that certain social groups - including single mothers -
will no longer be given priority treatment for accommodation. Some of Sir
George's proposals, which could be followed by legislation next year,
represent a substantial climbdown from ideas that were floated in a
consultation paper produced by the Department of the Environment six months
ago.
Labour said the plans were 'mean-spirited'. Shelter, the housing charity,
said they 'did nothing to increase the supply of affordable rented housing'.
Specific groups, including pregnant women and young people, will lose their
automatic right to permanent council accommodation. Ministers have regarded
the right as unfair to those with 'underlying needs' who are not made a
priority. They want most applications to be filtered through a single
waiting list.
The government also wants local authorities to ensure that applicants for
accommodation are 'unintentionally' homeless. Ministers say that a flaw of
the present system is that young people deliberately leave home and single
women deliberately become pregnant so that they can be eligible for
accommodation.
Sir George told MPs that vulnerable people would not be 'left to live on the
streets or in unsatisfactory accommodation'.
But Mr John Battle, his opposition counterpart, said that his statement
represented 'an attack on the basic rights to housing provision that not
even Mrs Thatcher . . . was prepared to contemplate'.
Mrs Sheila McKechnie, the director of Shelter, also criticised the
proposals. She said: 'We urge the government not to change the law. This can
only mean misery for the thousands of people in this country who are
currently homeless or living in poor conditions.'
Nevertheless, the government has softened some proposals from those in its
consultation paper:
Local authorities will still have discretion over how they allocate housing
 -providing accommodation for a single year to applicants who are judged to
be 'in priority need'.
The length of time that local authorities should provide accommodation is
longer than had been envisaged. Environment department officials stressed
that ministers had wanted to avoid the 'revolving door' syndrome, whereby
the homeless are constantly being shunted from one home to another.
Councils will have an obligation to extend accommodation to single mothers
living in women's hostels, against the recommendations of the consultation
paper.
</TEXT>
