<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JUL 94 / Tougher rules demanded on low-rent homes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Housing experts have called for tougher regulation of housing associations,
the voluntary organisations that provide almost all new low-cost homes for
rent.
Mr Anthony Mayer, chief executive of the Housing Corporation, the quango
that distributes government grants to associations, said yesterday that he
needed stronger powers to regulate housing association finances.
And in a report out today, Professor Valerie Karn of Manchester University
and Ms Linda Sheridan of Liverpool University call on the government to
impose minimum building standards on housing associations.
Mr Mayer said he had asked the government for stronger regulatory powers as
he launched the corporation's annual report. This showed that the number of
cases the corporation identified as requiring supervision last year was 81,
up from 44 in the previous year.
Mr Mayer said that the Department of the Environment would soon be
publishing a discussion paper on new powers for the corporation.
These would include proposals for faster intervention in associations when
financial problems arose. Mr Mayer said that the existing procedures for
intervening were 'cumbersome' and should be replaced by powers similar to
those of receivers in companies that went into liquidation.
The corporation wants associations to provide it with information on their
unregistered subsidiaries. These subsidiaries, often set up to build
low-cost homes for sale, can have a significant impact on association
performance.
The call for stricter regulation on building standards comes in a report
published by the Joseph Rowntree Foundation, the social research
organisation. The report says that building standards are falling. It says
most new homes have insufficient storage space and many lack enough space
for families to eat together.
The authors call on the government to specify minimum standards for housing
association homes.
Mr Greg Lomax, deputy chief executive of the corporation, said that the
research had been undertaken in 1991 and did not take account of
improvements made since then. Independent research carried out for the
corporation had indicated no cause for concern.
New Homes in the 1990s. Joseph Rowntree Foundation, 40 Water End, York YO3
6LP. Pounds 8.50.
