<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JUL 94 / Buenos Aires explosion kills 17
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CARMEN PIGNOTTI and AGENCIES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BUENOS AIRES
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Argentina closed its borders and placed police outside synagogues yesterday
after an explosion had ripped through the offices of a leading Jewish
organisation in Buenos Aires, killing at least 17 and injuring at least 127,
said a government official.
The blast, which nearly levelled the building, in a mainly Jewish district,
was a dramatic reminder of the attack two years ago on the Israeli embassy
in Buenos Aires, when a car bomb killed 30 people and injured some 250. The
source of that attack remains undiscovered.
President Carlos Menem initiated a high-level official inquiry yesterday and
instructed border guards to ground all flights and seal all borders.
Two foreigners were detained for questioning as they were about to board a
flight out of the country, said Mr Raul Burzaco, the presidential press
secretary. Telam, the domestic Argentine news agency, reported that they
were a German woman and an Iranian man, at Buenos Aires international
airport.
An estimated 100 people had worked in the building, which housed the
Delegation of Argentine-Israeli Associations, the country's principal Jewish
community organisation, and the Argentine Israelite Mutual Association, a
charity group.
There are some 250,000 Jews in Argentina, most of them in Buenos Aires.
In Jerusalem, Mr Shimon Peres, Israeli foreign minister, said he was sure
the explosion was a terrorist attack, while the World Jewish Congress in New
York called on all Jewish organisations to take immediate security
precautions.
Mr Yitzhak Rabin, Israeli prime minister, called the new attack 'a cowardly,
criminal and evil act'.
</TEXT>
