<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JUL 94 / Retail sales recover despite tax increases
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
An apparent rebound in retail sales last month coupled with a smaller than
expected government budget deficit in June have provided further evidence
that Britain remains on course for steady economic growth in spite of
April's tax increases.
In a report released today, the Confederation of British Industry said
retailers in June reported the strongest annual rate of sales volume growth
this year. They expect a similar rise in July.
Official figures, released yesterday, showed that the government's budget
deficit, or public sector borrowing requirement, was lower than expected at
Pounds 2.86bn in June.
According to economists, the drop in the PSBR from Pounds 4.3bn in May and
Pounds 3.95bn in June 1993 reflected accelerating economic growth as well as
gains from increased taxes imposed in both the 1993 Budgets. The growth rate
is suspected to be trimming unemployment and welfare costs as well as
increasing value added and income tax revenues.
The CBI said its survey of 502 companies in the retail, wholesale and motor
trades found sales volumes in the year to June rose at their strongest rate
since October 1988. The growth in the wholesale sector was especially
strong, led by demand for industrial materials.
Mr Nigel Whittaker, chairman of the CBI distributive trades panel, reported
a 'significant improvement' in the retailers' own assessment of their
business, although stocks remained higher than expected demand.
Mail order companies reported the strongest sales volume increase among
retailers while large multiple chains reported 'significant growth'. Small
chains, however, reported only a slight rise while, on balance, traders with
single outlets experienced a slight fall in sales.
Treasury on course, Page 8
Economy 'poised for success', says Clarke, Page 8
Feeling the pinch, Page 15
Exports must drive UK recovery, Page 15
Lex, Page 16
London stocks, Page 36
</TEXT>
