<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JUL 94 / Hymn for Mao hypes TV sets to China's masses
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Beijing Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A Chinese Communist party hymn written in honour of Chairman Mao Zedong has
been reborn as an advertising jingle glorifying a television set.
The song, rendered reverently throughout China after the Cultural
Revolution, begins: 'The sun is reddest, Chairman Mao is dearest.' But, in a
national television campaign, this has become: 'The sun is reddest, Long
Rainbow is newest.'
The shock to Chinese ears of recycling the revolutionary in the name of
commerce can hardly be imagined.
Mr Wang Xiren, a navy propaganda writer who penned the original lyrics soon
after Mao's death in 1976, said yesterday he would protest at the
commercialisation of his song. He wants the advertisement banned.
'The song revealed the people's love and reverence for Chairman Mao,' he
said. 'This distortion is irresponsible. It shows disrespect to the broad
masses.'
Mr Wang's song is famous among Chinese youth as well as those old enough to
remember life under Mao. Three years ago, it was featured on a new cassette
of Mao music, played on modern western instruments with the addition of a
funky beat.
Television viewers, nevertheless, are now wondering who would dare tamper
with the once sacred words under a regime which still officially venerates
Mao, and how they could get the jingle past the television censors.
The answer to both questions is hardly surprising in the emerging business
culture of modern China: the People's Liberation Army, which has embraced
the profit motive while retaining the political clout to cope with the
censors.
Long Rainbow is owned by the PLA's commercial arm, Norinco, and the factory,
at Mianyang city in Sichuan province, is a converted military radar plant
and uses Japanese technology under licence.
Ironically, the Long Rainbow plant came into existence because of one of
Chairman Mao's follies. In the late 1950s, he ordered that industries be
relocated to the interior from areas vulnerable to attack during a war that
never happened. The move left factories remote from markets and suppliers.
China is trying to revive many of these isolated inland enterprises by
upgrading their technology and turning military equipment factories to
civilian uses, including the production of consumer electronics.
Long Rainbow is one of the more successful examples of this policy.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>China North Industries Corp.
    Long Rainbow.
</CO>
<XX>
