<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JUL 94 / (CORRECTED) International Company News: Linotype-Hell cuts
deficit to DM57m in first half
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By AFX
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ESCHBORN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Correction (published 20th July 1994) appended to this article.
Linotype-Hell, the German printing machinery manufacturer, said its net loss
in the first six months narrowed to less than a quarter of the DM57m
(Dollars 35.6m) loss a year earlier, AFX reports from Eschborn.
The group said the result was in line with its aim of breaking even in the
full year. Sales in the six months were on target while new orders exceeded
expectations.
Linotype-Hell said more precise data on the company's first-half performance
would be published in August. The next six months should see further
improvement, the group said.
The planned break-even in 1994 would be achieved on a 'slight sales growth
compared with last year', the company added.
The restructuring, initiated in 1993, was largely responsible for the
narrower net loss in the first six months. In this period, Linotype-Hell's
US operations saw the strongest improvement in earnings to post a net profit
after a 'significant loss' a year earlier, the company said.
The company reported a 1993 net loss of DM153.4m after a net profit of
DM32.1m in 1992.
CORRECTION
Linotype-Hell, the German printing machinery manufacturer, reduced its net
loss in the first six months of the year to less than a quarter of the DM57m
(Dollars 35.6m) loss in the previous corresponding period. This was
incorrectly reported in a headline in yesterday's FT.
</TEXT>
